<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,618,644]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Slim and medium size (
<quantity box="[546,631,618,645]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" unit="mm" value="25.0">25 mm</quantity>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[650,714,619,645]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Head</emphasis>
elongated from a frontal view, curved from a side view, curving downward and backward. The mouthparts between hypognathous and opisthognathous 
<typeStatus box="[1144,1203,655,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">types</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[1220,1312,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
); very narrow space between antennal sockets, short fastigium, reduced and not visible ocelli, scapus, and pedicelus unarmed, maxillary palps moderately elongated. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[584,673,727,753]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Thorax</emphasis>
. Pronotum granular, sub-cylindrical (
<figureCitation box="[1091,1178,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
); lateral lobes are three times longer than high, humeral notch undeveloped (
<figureCitation box="[747,838,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[858,962,762,788]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Sternum</emphasis>
. Prosternum armed with two conspicuous triangular spines. Upper lobe of mesosternum medium-sized, surrounded by lateral lobes with elevated subtriangular edges, covering the base of meso-coxae. Metasternum with no elevated lateral lobes, covered in the anterior margin by the upper lobe, metafurcal sulcus moderately elongated and not curving abruptly. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1177,1253,870,896]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Wings</emphasis>
. Brachypterous, tegminae covering up to the second abdominal segment (
<figureCitation box="[783,860,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
A-B). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[931,987,907,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Legs</emphasis>
slim; front borders and middle legs well defined and delimited by a carina on each edge. Fore coxae armed with a dorsal spine, all coxae ventrally disarmed. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,978,1004]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Abdomen</emphasis>
without modifications on the posterior edge. Tenth tergite narrow and moderately sclerosed (more than the other abdominal tergites). Cerci are very robust and armed inner by preapical spines (
<figureCitation box="[1165,1244,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
C-D). Subgenital plate noticeably longer than wide, with articulated styles (
<figureCitation box="[800,890,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). Female unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1326,1086,1114]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" box="[199,1326,1086,1114]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,1086,1113]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Taxa included.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Beier, 1962)" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Beier" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[381,777,1087,1114]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[381,621,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pepumiri brasiliensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Beier, M." box="[636,768,1087,1114]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" pagination="468" refId="ref3769" refString="Beier, M. (1962) Orthoptera Tettigoniidae (Pseudophyllinae I). In: Mertens, R., Hennig, W. &amp; Wermuth, H. (Eds.), Das Tierreich. Vol. 73. Walter de Gruyter &amp; Co., Berlin, pp. 468." type="book chapter" year="1962">Beier, 1962</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[783,885,1087,1113]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[783,885,1087,1113]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
