</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1123,1149]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name is an arbitrary combination of letters derived from two words in the Brazilian indigenous language Tupi: 
<emphasis box="[326,380,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">pépó</emphasis>
= wings + 
<emphasis box="[509,556,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">mirĩ</emphasis>
= small, and it refers to the katydids’ small-sized wings. This name is neither non-Latin nor Greek, and gender is established as neuter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,782,1230,1258]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" box="[199,782,1230,1258]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1230,1256]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion box="[359,427,1231,1257]" country="Brazil" name="Goias" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Goiás</collectingRegion>
, Veadeiros (Brazilian Cerrado).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1266,1292]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Comparison</emphasis>
. The 
<taxonomicName authority="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza, 2022" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" box="[415,519,1267,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[415,519,1267,1292]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pepumiri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[529,610,1267,1293]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[529,610,1267,1293]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, characteristics are distinctive and well-differentiated from other genera from the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" box="[319,439,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pleminiini">Pleminiini</taxonomicName>
. Compared to other genera of brachypterous species, such as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Redtenbacher" authorityYear="1895" box="[1150,1276,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1150,1276,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Dasyscelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Stal, 1874" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1874" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pleminia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1335,1436,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pleminia</emphasis>
Stål, 1874
</taxonomicName>
, these specimens have triangular and lamellar spines on the legs. Furthermore, the head and mouthparts are hypognate, unlike the 
<taxonomicName authority="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza, 2022" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" box="[440,544,1375,1400]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[440,544,1375,1400]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pepumiri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[551,629,1375,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[551,629,1375,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, located behind, almost on the thoracic sternites. The tegminae venation in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Redtenbacher" authorityYear="1895" box="[180,306,1411,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[180,306,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Dasyscelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1874" box="[362,463,1411,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pleminia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[362,463,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pleminia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is less reticulated and has larger spaces between the longitudinal and transverse veins. Known males from the last two genera have short and slightly thickened stridulation crest, in contrast to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Beier" baseAuthorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">P. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[187,289,1483,1509]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[187,289,1483,1509]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, which have an elongated and thickened stridulation crest. The cerci of the males of this new genus are very distinctive because the cerci of other genera compared here are cylindrical, with similar thickness throughout their length and a distal spine, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Beier" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[563,720,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[563,720,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">P. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[727,829,1555,1581]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[727,829,1555,1581]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has thickened cerci and two preapical spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1590,1616]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Comments.</emphasis>
We include 
<taxonomicName authority="Beier, 1962" authorityName="Beier" authorityYear="1962" box="[478,910,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis box="[478,771,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Dasyscelidius brasiliensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Beier, M." box="[779,910,1591,1617]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" pagination="468" refId="ref3769" refString="Beier, M. (1962) Orthoptera Tettigoniidae (Pseudophyllinae I). In: Mertens, R., Hennig, W. &amp; Wermuth, H. (Eds.), Das Tierreich. Vol. 73. Walter de Gruyter &amp; Co., Berlin, pp. 468." type="book chapter" year="1962">Beier, 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
as the only known species and as a new combination of 
<taxonomicName authority="This" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" box="[282,386,1627,1652]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[282,386,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pepumiri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[394,474,1627,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[394,474,1627,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
This species inhabits the Cerrado ecoregion in 
<collectingCountry box="[1013,1086,1627,1653]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: vast savanna whose higher elevation areas have humid conditions, ideal for species such as 
